article.headline: McWilliams-Franklin scores 18, grabs 14 boards
article.story:
INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- Taj McWilliams-Franklin has regained her
touch at the right time.

She had 18 points and a season-high 14 rebounds, leading the
Connecticut Sun past the Indiana Fever 63-58 Tuesday night.

"The last two or three games she's gotten better and better.
She's finally getting her balance back. She was shooting so much
off balance," Connecticut coach Mike Thibault said. "She's got
her stroke back a little bit."

McWilliams-Franklin has 46 points in her last three games,
raising her average this season to 11.2. Her rebound total was just
one short of the franchise record and was the most this season by a
Connecticut player.

"We had good passing tonight to the post," said
McWilliams-Franklin, who also helped limit Indiana center Natalie
Williams to just four points on 2-of-10 shooting and four rebounds.

Tamika Catchings, with 19 points, scored in double figures for
the 36th consecutive game. The Indiana star has been in double
figures in every game since last June 23.

Connecticut led by eight points early in the second half after
taking its biggest lead of the night at 36-26 late in the first
half. Indiana cut the deficit to 48-47 on a 3-pointer by Coretta
Brown, then to 55-54 on a 3 by Kelly Miller.

Nykesha Sales then scored six straight points for the Sun,
giving Connecticut a 61-56 edge with 2:55 remaining. Indiana never
drew closer than three points thereafter.

"We didn't make our perimeter shots. We panicked at the end and
took shots that we should not have," Indiana coach Brian Winters
said. "We had opportunities around the rim that didn't go in."

Deanna Jackson was the only other Indiana player in double
figures with 12 points. The Sun had three other players in double
figures. Wendy Palmer scored 14, while Sales and reserve Asjha
Jones had 10 apiece.

The Sun led 38-32 at halftime after shooting 50 percent
(14-of-28). Connecticut outrebounded Indiana 15-12 in the first
half, although the Fever had come into the game leading the league
with a .542 rebounding percentage.

For the game, Connecticut had a 32-29 advantage off the boards.
